Iraqis faced escalating violence as they prepared to vote in a historic election.
Insurgents targeted polling stations, killing civilians and security forces.
Despite security measures, attacks persisted, with suicide bombings claiming lives.
The US and UK planned troop withdrawal as tensions mounted.
President Bush urged Iraqis to seize the opportunity to vote.
Al-Qaeda threatened further bloodshed, with attacks intensifying on election eve.
Security forces tightened measures, but violence persisted, with casualties reported.
The election marked a pivotal moment for Iraq, marred by fear and bloodshed, as the nation braved threats to embrace democracy.
